Exploring the ford go bike dataset¶

by Jagdeep Singh¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

The dataset looks at the ford go bikes for the year 2017. It will be interesting to see what locations and possible routes are most used to help make decisions for future expansion or realocation of bikes.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There were originally 519700 bike trips that were recorded with 15 features (duration (s), start time, end time, start station id, start stationname, start station latitude, start station longitude, end station id, end station name, end station latitude, end station longitude, bike id, user type, member birth year, member gender)

On inspection, 66541 bike trips were found to have incomplete data and therefore had to be removed before analysis. This meant a 13% reduction in the dataset.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

It would be interesting to find out the type of users that ride bikes. For example, what it the distribution of user age or are majority male or female. In addition visuallising the duration of bike rides may give us some insight on how long people prefer to ride a bike. Finally, looking at which stations the bikes start and end may give us some insight on regular/poppular journeys and so bike distribution can be more strategic

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I can start by looking at the distribution of user's birth year, user's gender and bike ride duration. Then I can look at the start and end stations to determine popular stations/routes.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

During the univirate exploration there where some points that where unusual, such as when the age was plotted it wasn't very clear. The graph showed what year someone was born in but it was hard to determin thier age. So 2019 - birth year gave a better idea of someones age at first glance. I wanted to see what stations where the most popular but when this was plotted there were too many staions and it was messy and crowded. The station names were also too large to be seen clearly so they were rotated.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Some of the values in the gender column were missing and therefore needed removing. There were too many values for the different stations all acorss the city so it was better to just look at the most popular few. This was done by only allowing the stations which get the most use to be plotted.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The first comparison made was to see if the most used stations are also linked to the longest duration bike rides. As this was positive corrolation when plotted it can be seen as being true. The second comparision was made to see if the genders had a difference in proprtion when it came to subscribers vs customers. The finding were that there are more males taht use the service then women in both catagories but far more subcribers use the service compared to customers for all genders.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

Out of curiosity I had a look at a heat map for all the values in the dataset. It was interesting to see what interactions were made by all the different elements, some had a positive correlation, some had a negative one and others had no correlation at all. It was useful to see what elements would work with each other.

Looking at ride duration and member age along with gender gave a interesting insight as it showed a steady decline in how long a ride would last and the members age.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

When looking at all the stations separatly it was interesting to see that there was similarites between the first comparison and this one but more detail to see the out lyers. For instance seeing multiple members in thier 60s, using the bikes for long duration rides.
